MissionCommands.Message: Good day {{profileName}}, how's everything in {{capsuleName}}?? I bet you are excited to get up there again?
Good day! Yes indeed, this spaceship flies like a dream! I wonder when they will let you give it a try?
Don't get cheeky on me {{profileName}}, just heard the word I'm scheduled for the next flight, a long duration flight.
Sounds good Patrick.
Ok, we are ready here, let's get this going. The backup crew has set up the capsule.
Roger. {{coPilotName}}, let's do this.
OK, complete the pre-flight checklist and press PROCEED when ready.
Ready to proceed. Mission Control, cockpit setup.
Roger. Go through the mission briefing and use timescale towards ignition.
Roger, will do.
T-60 seconds, verify platform alignment and that the D-Rings are installed.
Ok Titan, show us what you can do!
T-20 seconds. Prepare the ascent checklist and follow it during the ascent.
Bolts and liftoff!
Verify clocks are counting and monitor ascent.
We are on our way to orbit!
Staging!
Roger staging.
Curious on the Hand-Held Maneuvering Unit (HHMU) and how it works while weightless.
Well, we know it has 30 seconds of fuel, should be enough to see how it works, and if we can make it to the backpack.
Good thing that backpack has some additional fuel. The HHMU is used to translate forward or backwards in the direction you look. Attitude is changed using normal attitude controls.
Yeah. Procedures are to turn off the OAMS and venting the cabin before opening the hatch, and exiting the craft.
Yes. But first, let's get this into the target orbit and complete the ascent. Check the systems.
Roger, preparing for insertion.
SECO!
Roger SECO, separate the stage and follow procedures.
Ok, we need to separate the spacecraft from the LV and remove the sensor covers.
Separation, will enable OAMS and zero the IVI's.
Roger, press PROCEED when ready.
Ok, performing the insertion checklist.
Roger insertion checklist, press PROCEED when ready.
Checklist complete. Mission Control, spacecraft configured for orbital operations.
Roger. We will do perform the EVA at MET 60 minutes, and the flight mode test now. We will start with the RATE COMMAND flight mode.
Ok, let's turn on the OAMS using the OAMS enable checklist, and then set the control mode to RATE COMMAND.
Roger, attitude control set to RATE COMMAND.
Spend 60 seconds getting familiar with how this mode functions, then move over to DIRECT mode.
Ok, next is the DIRECT mode. In this mode, you are fully responsible for all attitude forces yourself. Use small inputs and thrusts to change the attitude for about 60 seconds.
Ok, DIRECT mode set.
Maneuver to prograde attitude and maintain prograde attitude for about two minutes.
Ok, switch to SEF and take a small break before we start preparing for the EVA. We will start at MET 60 minutes, just above Australia.
Roger.
{{profileName}}, you ready for your EVA?
Was just thinking about it, will let Mission Control know we are ready.
Mission Control, we are ready to start the procedures for the EVA.
Roger. We just had a slight delay, but we are ready for you. Shut down the OAMS and follow the EVA checklist.
Use the RUN feature to complete the Pre-EVA checklist.
Roger, preparing for EVA.
Run the DEPRESS-EGRESS checklist and get ready to egress.
Roger, final preparations for egress.
Checklist complete. Performing EVA.
Ok, I have stepped out of the spacecraft, will give the HHMU a try.

Roger. Be careful and spend as little fuel as possible. Try to get that backpack if you can, but that's optional, make sure you return back into the capsule in time by using the COMM/TOOLs menu and press Enter.
Roger, I'm drifting outside the capsule now.
Use the HHMU to translate forward or backwards in the direction you are facing. You can peek around using the right mouse button (default mapping).
Roger, comms working great.
Try to avoid hitting the spacecraft too much, or else I will start to get sick in here.
Feels like a roller coaster?
Most likely. I'll give you some space to give that backpack retrieval a try. Return inside when ready.
Welcome back, you made it!
Yes sure, that was fun!
Mission Control, I'm back in the capsule now. I would say the HHMU worked well as long as I used it relative to my center of gravity.
Roger, we are glad to hear that. Had a few blue faces down here. Can't wait to get a full report at the debriefing. Bring that capsule home.
Roger, will do!
Let's close those hatches and get this cockpit back to orbital operations mode. Complete the Post-EVA checklist using the RUN feature.
Roger, let's pressurize this cabin again.

We wish to splash down in the Atlantic, so our retrograde burn should be on the west coast of the U.S. Again, using the Orbital Cursor on Orbit View (F3), drag the slider so it's position is above the coast.

Then use timescale so that our spacecraft passes the orbital cursor. We want to complete a full orbit in this mission and have enough time for entry preparations. Press ROGER when orbital cursor is passed.
Then get back into the cockpit view, and request that our retrograde burn should happen on the orbital cursor point. Press DONE! when ready.
We should now have a retrograde burn time. We will start the PRE RETRO checklist 30 minutes before ignition.
We are 30 minutes from retrograde burn. Proceed with the PRE RETRO burn using the RUN feature.
Going through the checklist now.
Checklist complete. Will proceed with the normal entry procedures.
Adapter is separated.
Roger, adapter separation complete.
Excellent, retros are burning! Burn lasts 20 seconds. Proceed with retro checklist.
Retros jettisoned, complete the POST-RETRO JETTISON checklist.
We are getting ready for atmospheric entry.
Roger. Good luck. Follow procedures.
Ok, we are having some G's
Hold tight!
Ugh.
{{capsuleName}}, do you read?
Things are simmering down. Follow the landing checklist and prepare for drogue release.
This is {{capsuleName}}, loud and clear. Do you read?
Loud and clear!
Roger! Great to see you, we have a visual. Welcome back!
Roger. Waiting for drogue.
And there she flies!
Roger drogue!
Ok, we see them. Set landing attitude and prepare for splashdown.
Roger.
We have splash down at this time.
Not bad! Complete the POST-LANDING checklist.
Preparing for recovery, we are all in good shape.
Roger, welcome home, and congratulations with ANOTHER first.
Thank you! What's the score again?
Oh, I'll see you at the debrief. This is MCC signing out, recovery will take over. (Transmission ends)

MissionGoals.Description: Get the backpack from the rear of the ship.

Title: WALK IN SPACE
Description: Extra-vehicular activity (EVA) aka. spacewalk is mandatory in Project Apollo, where astronauts will need to leave the spacecraft and walk on the Moon. This mission is designed to support this and learn how you are able to work outside the spacecraft in Earth orbit.
BriefingText:
BRIEFING

In this mission you will be launched into an initial elliptical orbit of 161km x 225 km.

After insertion, you will spend a few minutes getting familiar with attitude control in both DIRECT and RATE COMMAND mode. This will simulate how the EVA controls work.

At MET 60 minutes, you will perform an EVA with the task of retrieving a backpack located at the rear end of the spaceship. To retrieve it, press the GET button above the backpack.

After the EVA, we will return back home.

EVA CONTROLS
Use the Hand-Held Maneuvering Unit (HHMU) to translate forward and backwards using normal translation controls, and change your orientation using the normal attitude controls.

Once you move in a direction, there is no force that will stop you so you will need to counter with the opposite direction to stop or change direction.
Avoid hitting the capsule with too high velocity, or else Newtons third law will add force back to the ship, and it will start drifting.

Good luck!
